  "doc_id": "13141",
  "text": "After their MRI study, [CITATION_1] Itoi et al 5 carried out a preliminary prospective clinical study. They assigned 40 patients with primary dislocations either to conventional immobilisation in internal rotation or to immobilisation in 10° of external rotation. Initially, they attempted to immobilise the shoulder in 30° of external rotation, but this was not well tolerated by the patients. Therefore they decreased the angle of external rotation \"arbitrarily down to 10°\". The rate of recurrence was 30% in the internal rotation group and zero in those in external rotation at a mean follow-up of 15.5 months. In subjects under the age of 30 years there was a rate of recurrence of 45% in the internal rotation and of zero in the external rotation group.",
